(1158, 128, '_titre_mission', 'field_532d77e706dcf'),
(1159, 128, 'descriptif_mission', '<b>While remaining open to various theoretical approaches, Lentic\'s research is based on data obtained from observing and analyzing situations of organizational change: </b>\r\n\r\n<b>The Contingency Approach</b>, which values the coherence of managerial internal and external choices. As regards HRM, this approach contributes to examining the mutual coherence of HRM actions with reference to the various conventions obtained from research (Pichault et Nizet, 2013); it also assesses the articulation of HRM conventions and concrete organizational functioning given that the former largely depend on the latter rather than conversely (Nizet et Pichault, 2001);\r\n\r\n<b>The \"political\" approach</b> (Pichault, 2013), for which the divergence of interests underlies all organizational functioning.  The approach also seeks to identifies the various stakeholders in a given situation, and to examine if not anticipate their assets, abilitites to team up and their reactions to the change projects affecting them.\r\n\r\n<b>The \"contextualist\" approach</b> (Brouwers, Cornet, Guttierez, Pichault, Rousseau et Warnotte, 1997), which considers all contexts of change the product of an interaction between a content subject to mutation (as regards HRM, of an organization, of information technologies, etc.), a context (both internal and external) and a process (actors\' interactions mobilizing the contextual elements with a view to influence the evolution of the content according to their interests, the \"translations\" thus occurring between their particular objectives, etc.)\r\n\r\nLENTIC is deeply convinced that such theoretical knowledge can become efficient management tools for guiding the direction of change (Rorive, 2003).'),
